This directory contains an example, that shows the usage of
the standard ConceptBase Servlets.

FILES
=====

README: this file
Paper.sml: Class and Query definitions for this example
PaperInst.sml: Some instances for the class Paper
PaperForm.html: An HTML to insert papers
default.cfg: Configuration file for JSDK 2.1
runservlets: Script to start the servletrunner (JSDK 2.0) or the web server (JSDK 2.1)
servlet.properties: Servlet Properties for JSDK 2.0
servlets.properties: Servlet Properties for JSDK 2.1


INSTALLATION
============

First, check which version of the Java Servlet Development Kit (JSDK) you have
installed. They are currently two versions of the JSDK (2.0 and 2.1) which
require slightly different configurations, but the servlet code is for both
versions identical. 

Edit the script "runservlets", so that the correct JSDK version is used.

Start a ConceptBase server and load the files "Paper.sml" and "PaperInst.sml".


For JSDK 2.0
============

The configuration file for JSDK 2.0 is "servlet.properties". Change in this
file the settings for hostname, portnumber (of the ConceptBase server) and log directory
if needed. The script "runservlets" will then start the "servletrunner" of JSDK 2.0. 
The "servletrunner" of JSDK 2.0 is just able to execute servlets,
and is not a "full" web server, as the one in JSDK 2.1.

Because of this, the file "PaperForm.html" must be placed at a location
where it can be accessed with a web browser. The "action" method in the
form (line 7), and the link to the list of all papers (line 34) must therefore
be changed to reflect the actual location of the servletrunner
(i.e. http://host:port/servlet/...).


For JSDK 2.1
============

Configuration for JSDK 2.1 is little bit more complicated. The file
"default.cfg" specifies the port number, inet address, document base directory
etc. which are used by the web server. Create a subdirectory "webpages"
and copy the file "PaperForm.html" into this directory. Furthermore, create
in the directory "webpages" a subdirectory "WEB-INF" and copy the file
"servlets.properties" into this directory. Edit the file to adjust it
to your local settings.

Then go back to the directory with the script "runservlets" and execute it.
It should start up a "full" web server, the example form can then be accessed
at http://host:port/PaperForm.html .


More Information
================

More information on the configuration of the JSDK can be found in the Java
Tutorial at http://java.sun.com/docs/books/tutorial/index.html .
If you need detailed information of the ConceptBase servlets, ask
the ConceptBase Team (cb@i5.informatik.rwth-aachen.de) for more information.

